        <section id="technical-details">
            <h2 class="section-title">Technical Implementation</h2>
            <p>Each project followed a consistent production pipeline, adapted to the specific format and audience:</p>

            <div class="method-box">
                <h4>Phase 1: Analysis & Scripting</h4>
                <p>Worked with subject matter experts (SMEs) and stakeholders to define learning objectives, target audience, and appropriate modality. Produced detailed scripts, storyboards and POCs as part of the pre-production process.</p>

                <h4>Phase 2: eLearning & Multimedia Production</h4>
                <p>Recorded professional voiceover narration, edited screen recordings and animations in Camtasia, and assembled final video(s) or interactive content using authoring tools such Captivate or Articulate 360.</p>

                <h4>Phase 3: LMS Publishing</h4>
                <p>Packaged videos and/or completed eLearning courses (often utilizing SCORM) and published them to the company's LMS. Configured enrollment/asssignment rules, completion tracking, and reporting. Hosted supplemental video content via SharePoint and embedded links within course shells.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="challenges">
            <h2 class="section-title">Key Factors</h2>
            <div class="case-study">
                <p><strong>Change Management:</strong> Many of the projects required building training for tools and processes that were simultaneously being rolled out company-wide — meaning content had to be produced before workflows were fully stabilized. Change Management was a major element in most of these projects.</p>
                <p><strong>Agile Methodology:</strong> Adopted a modular content design approach, keeping individual topics short and self-contained so modules could be updated or swapped without rebuilding entire courses. Close collaboration with SMEs during active rollouts allowed for iterative revisions. Worked with pilot cohorts to generate feedback that shaped the final published versions. Agile/rapid development became especially crucial during the months after the company transitioned to a heavy work-from-home context in March of 2020.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="outcomes">
            <h2 class="section-title">Outcomes & Skills</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>End-to-End Production:</strong> Owned the full instructional design lifecycle from needs analysis and scripting through production, QA, and LMS publishing.</li>
                <li><strong>Multimedia Creation:</strong> applied professional narration, screen capture, animation, and video editing skills across a diverse library of training content.</li>
                <li><strong>WFH/Office 365 Adoption:</strong> Built adoption-focused learning content for Office 365 (including SharePoint and Microsoft Teams). These programs helped facilitate a smooth transition to a sudden shift to a 100% work-from-home model in March of 2020.</li>
                <li><strong>Agile:</strong> Translated Agile/Scrum concepts into accessible, engaging learning opportunities for technical and non-technical audiences. Agile methodologies were also a major component of my team's content development process, which championed an ADDIE-centric approach.</li>
                <li><strong>Storytelling for Learning:</strong> Applied creative, scenario-based techniques (such as the "Laptop Drop" and "Life of a Claim" modules) to increase learner engagement with otherwise dry procedural content.</li>
                <li><strong>LMS migration:</strong> I helped lead the transitiion to a new enterprise learning management system. This included participating in the new LMS selection process and migrating/transferring content to the new system.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> A robust library of training content spanning methodology, enterprise initiatives, and eLearning programs — all produced in-house, accelerating production time and increasing agility for new training initiatives.</p>
